These developments, and future shocks, have the potential to be amplified by vulnerabilities associated with asset valuations, borrowing by households and businesses, financial leverage, and funding risks. https://t.co/geK1HBF0Bw (5/5)

A weaker outlook, higher interest rates, and uncertainty contributed to tightening financial conditions. Economic, financial, and geopolitical risks rose across advanced and emerging market economies, contributing to asset price declines and periods of market volatility. (4/5)

Since the May 2022 report, uncertainty about the economic outlook has remained elevated. Inflation remains high in the United States & in many other countries. Central banks around the world, including the Federal Reserve, have tightened monetary policy in response. (3/5)

The Financial Stability report reviews conditions affecting the stability of the financial system. The @federalreserve monitors risks to the financial system & works to help ensure a healthy economy for U.S. households, communities, & businesses. https://t.co/nwczNpXcgT (2/5) https://t.co/EPF0VsNifF

tweet_text: While the Federal Reserve has made no decisions on whether to pursue or implement a central bank digital currency, or CBDC, we have been exploring the potential benefits & risks of CBDCs from a variety of angles, including through technological research & experimentation. (2/3)

Uncertainty over the inflation outlook poses risks to financial conditions and economic activity. Against this backdrop, financial markets experienced high volatility and some strains on market liquidity. (5/5) Learn more: https://t.co/nwczNpXcgT

In the near term, the invasion is likely to create additional upward pressure on inflation. After deteriorating early in the period because of the spread of the Omicron variant, the pandemic outlook has improved but remains uncertain.  (4/5) Learn more: https://t.co/nwczNpF32L

Since the November 2021 report, uncertainty about the economic outlook has increased. The Russian invasion of Ukraine has caused tremendous human and economic hardship, and the implications for the U.S. and global economies are highly uncertain. (3/5) https://t.co/nwczNpXcgT

The Financial Stability report which reviews conditions affecting the stability of the financial system. Promoting financial stability is a key element in meeting the dual mandate for monetary policy regarding full employment & stable prices. (2/5) https://t.co/nwczNpF32L

The Federal Reserve is the central bank of the United States. It performs five key economic functions in the public interest to help promote the healthy U.S. economy, including promoting the stability of a financial system. Learn more: (1/5) https://t.co/dGvcR4aFjG

Would a U.S. CBDC replace cash or paper currency? The Federal Reserve is committed to ensuring continued safety, availability of cash; considering CBDC as means to expand safe payment options, not to reduce, replace them. tweet_text: Funding risk. Funding risks at domestic banks remain low, because these banks rely only modestly on short-term wholesale funding and maintain sizable holdings of high-quality liquid assets. (5/5) https://t.co/7yvooMSPi5

Banks remain well capitalized. Measures of hedge fund leverage are somewhat above historical averages. Amid elevated investor risk appetite, issuance of collateralized loan obligations & asset-backed securities has been robust. (4/5) https://t.co/JdIK6Dyi3v

Borrowing: Debt owed by businesses was effectively flat in 2nd half of 2020, remaining at a high level relative to GDP. Improving earnings, low interest rates, & ongoing gov support have increased ability of businesses to service these obligations. (3/5) https://t.co/w9VbmJlqz4

Our current view of vulnerabilities is as follows: Asset valuations. Prices of risky assets have generally increased since November with improving fundamentals, and, in some markets, prices are high compared with expected cash flows. (2/5) Learn more: https://t.co/fplMLzYYNx

#ICYMI The Financial Stability report reviews conditions affecting the stability of the financial system by analyzing vulnerabilities related to valuation pressures, borrowing by businesses & households, financial leverage, & funding risk. (1/5) https://t.co/TmM64JriKc

tweet_text: Because of the restrictions put in place by the Board from the first stress test, banks have built capital, allowing them to continue lending. Since the future of the economy is still uncertain, the restrictions will be kept w/ modifications. (4/4) https://t.co/MGrRK0nLds

Today’s results of that second stress test show that firms remain well capitalized under two hypothetical severe recessions. They feature severe global downturns with substantial stress in financial markets that serve to capture a broad set of severe but plausible risks. (3/4)

However, the future of the economy, and how it might affect the health of banks, was very uncertain. As a result, the Board put several restrictions on banks and then announced a second stress test later in the year. (2/4)

In June, the @federalreserve released the results of its annual supervisory stress test. Those results indicated that the banking sector was generally well capitalized, which would allow banks to continue lending to businesses & households during a severe recession. (1/4)
